      <!-- Section 1: Word List Memorisation Order -->
      <h2 class="text-xl font-light text-amber-600 dark:text-amber-400 mt-10 mb-4 border-l-4 border-amber-400 pl-4">The Word List Memorisation Ladder</h2>

      <p>Every pro player follows a similar progression. The key insight: learn the words that give you the most scoring power per hour of study first. A Scrabble dictionary contains over 270,000 words — you cannot memorise them all at once, but you can prioritise ruthlessly.</p>

      <div class="not-prose my-6 p-5 rounded-xl border border-purple-500/30 bg-purple-950/10">
        <p class="text-sm font-semibold text-purple-400 uppercase tracking-wider mb-3">🧩 Memorisation Order (Follow This Exactly)</p>
        <div class="space-y-3">
          <div class="flex items-start gap-3">
            <span class="shrink-0 w-6 h-6 rounded-full bg-purple-900/50 border border-purple-500/40 flex items-center justify-center text-xs text-purple-300 font-bold">1</span>
            <p class="text-sm text-gray-300"><strong class="text-white">107 Two-Letter Words</strong> — the foundation. These open parallel plays, create hooks, and let you score in tight board positions. Master these in week one.</p>
          </div>
          <div class="flex items-start gap-3">
            <span class="shrink-0 w-6 h-6 rounded-full bg-purple-900/50 border border-purple-500/40 flex items-center justify-center text-xs text-purple-300 font-bold">2</span>
            <p class="text-sm text-gray-300"><strong class="text-white">Q-without-U Words</strong> — QI, QOPH, QADI, QAID, QANAT, QINTAR. The Q tile is worth 10 points but deadly if stuck. These words eliminate that risk entirely.</p>
          </div>
          <div class="flex items-start gap-3">
            <span class="shrink-0 w-6 h-6 rounded-full bg-purple-900/50 border border-purple-500/40 flex items-center justify-center text-xs text-purple-300 font-bold">3</span>
            <p class="text-sm text-gray-300"><strong class="text-white">High-Value 3-Letter Words</strong> — ZAX, ZEK, JOE, QUA, XI, XU. Three-letter words with J, X, Z, Q that consistently score 25-40 points on premium squares.</p>
          </div>
          <div class="flex items-start gap-3">
            <span class="shrink-0 w-6 h-6 rounded-full bg-purple-900/50 border border-purple-500/40 flex items-center justify-center text-xs text-purple-300 font-bold">4</span>
            <p class="text-sm text-gray-300"><strong class="text-white">Scrabble Hook Words</strong> — single letters that transform existing words (e.g., adding S, D, R, or rare hooks like adding C to LUMP → CLUMP). These let you score on two words simultaneously.</p>
          </div>
          <div class="flex items-start gap-3">
            <span class="shrink-0 w-6 h-6 rounded-full bg-purple-900/50 border border-purple-500/40 flex items-center justify-center text-xs text-purple-300 font-bold">5</span>
            <p class="text-sm text-gray-300"><strong class="text-white">7-Letter Bingo Stems</strong> — SATIRE, RETAIN, NASTIER, TRAINED, ASTERIN. Learn the top 100 stems that combine with any letter to form valid 7 letter bingos worth 50+ bonus points.</p>
          </div>
          <div class="flex items-start gap-3">
            <span class="shrink-0 w-6 h-6 rounded-full bg-purple-900/50 border border-purple-500/40 flex items-center justify-center text-xs text-purple-300 font-bold">6</span>
            <p class="text-sm text-gray-300"><strong class="text-white">4–5 Letter Power Words</strong> — common plays using high-value tiles. Words like JAZZY, FIZZY, PIZZA, QUAFF. Use a Scrabble word generator to test yourself on these racks daily.</p>
          </div>
          <div class="flex items-start gap-3">
            <span class="shrink-0 w-6 h-6 rounded-full bg-purple-900/50 border border-purple-500/40 flex items-center justify-center text-xs text-purple-300 font-bold">7</span>
            <p class="text-sm text-gray-300"><strong class="text-white">Full Dictionary Deep Dive</strong> — SOWPODS (267,000+) or TWL (187,000+). At this stage you are memorising by word pattern, not individual words. Use an instant Scrabble solver to verify recall accuracy.</p>
          </div>
